                            <strong>Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)</strong> is a long-term progressive lung disease that causes difficulty breathing. Chronic bronchitis and emphysema are types of COPD.
                            In 2004, about 64 million people worldwide were living with COPD.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Risk factors for COPD include:
                            <ul>
                                <li>Smoking or passive smoking</li>
                                <li>Lung irritants such as chemical fumes</li>
                                <li>Family history, with AATD gene linked to COPD</li>
                                <li>History of respiratory tract infections in childhood</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            There is no cure for COPD, but the progression of the disease can be slowed with medication. The best way to prevent COPD is to stop smoking and avoid secondhand smoke and other lung irritants.
